node.text: I love garden tools...so much so that I probably have about 40 in my shed right now. But as a beginner, you only need about 3 - a cutting tool, digging tool, and watering tool. As you expand your garden, you may want to get into long-handled tools or specialty tools, so I've also included those in this video. At the end, a bit of a bonus on how I sharpen my tools to keep them working for years and years.

node.title: 12 Essential Gardening Tools for Beginner and Advanced Gardeners

node.text:
Honored and humbled to bring you this collaboration with @charles_dowding - we released the full version on YouTube, including Zoom conversations with each other before and after building our no-dig beds. The idea was, "How do you build a no-dig bed based on your unique climate?"

You'll see some differences in approach between myself and Charles, though I will say most of the differences are missteps in my technique - Charles has perfected his methods and in the video you'll see me note the adjustments I'll be making on future beds.

I truly hope this helps you kick off the new year feeling empowered to start growing a bit of your own food, even if you don't have much in the way of resources to buy "fancy" garden products.

Keep on growing,
Kevin

node.text:
🍅 TOMATO STORAGE 🍅 Here's a quick and simple tomato storage tip that should extend the life of your juicy, delicious tomatoes, especially the bug chinky heirlooms!

Just store it with the stem side down. That's it! The blossom end of the tomato ripens first, so storing that side down means the side that will get squishiest first is on the bottom.

On top of that, just due to the structure of the tomato, storing upside down allows for better weight distribution across the shoulders of the tomato instead of it all concentrating on one point, the bottom blossom end.

Should help them last a bit longer 👌🏽

node.text:
The garden in peak summer. I'm pretty sure I am way too harsh on myself in pretty much everything I do, but simultaneously seem unable to stop being that way.

The garden's never good enough, the business is never strong enough, the content isn't compelling enough, and so on. In many ways this obsession has led to be success of Epic Gardening, which is far beyond where I could have ever imagined. At the same time it is not the most healthy long-term mentality to hold throughout life.

Today I sat in a chair in my backyard for a while, looking at the wind rustling through the herb garden with absolutely zero thoughts in my head and realized how long it's been since I've done anything like that.

What's the point of building if you don't enjoy what you built? A constant reminder for myself, and perhaps you too if you relate.

Taking the weekend off! 

Keep on growing, Kevin

GARDEN UPDATE! It's crazy how fast a garden can grow when you set it up for success from the start and you have a diligent gardener tending to it 💯

@kehlani garden is absolutely popping off with growth in just a month since @jacquesinthegarden and I set it up 👀.

Corn is over head high, salsa garden is nearing first harvest, beans are exploding, and @kehlani is getting her first squash - and about to learn the classic summer gardener's dilemma: what the 🤬 are you supposed to do with all the squash 😂.

So awesome to see the progress...can't wait to pop up for a harvest 💯

node.text:
🌽 CORN HARVEST 🌽 So far, the corn this year have gone off without a hitch! I amended the old potato patch with a ton of feather meal and blood meal, and it looks like the blood meal won out. That makes sense given it’s higher nitrogen content and the fact that corn, being a grass, is an extremely heavy nitrogen feeder.

This little ear was from an offshoot off of the main stalk - the main ear of corn was roughly twice the size!

The indicators I use for harvest are the color of the silks turning brown and the texture of them shriveling up, as well as some kernels at the top popping with a milky liquid. If you have those indicators, generally you are good to go! You can also give your ear a firm squeeze to test the kernel development inside.

I don’t see too many people do this, but you can also just eat your sweet corn raw right out of the garden! It can sometimes cause a little bit of an upset stomach, but to me I seem to handle it well and it is absolutely delicious 💯

TOMATO PRUNING UPDATE - It’s been at least a month since I last updated you on my tomato pruning experiment. It’s the same exact tomato, so the genetics are the same. But you can see the one that I let go wild has continued to get even more wild, ripening fruits from the bottom trusses upwards.

On the tomato I pruned to a single leader stem, I got fruits two or three weeks earlier, but there are less overall fruit.

Honestly, whether you prune or not it’s totally up to you, but I personally prefer less fruit of more varieties, so I will tend to prune mine to 1 to 3 main stems.

What’s your preference?

Big tomato trellis is the Titan Tomato Cage from @gardeners

DOG VOMIT SLIME MOLD! Winner of the “most appealing name” award, this slime mold terrifies new gardeners. I get a ton of messages about it!

Fear not...it’s effectively harmless and often shows up on your mulch, with wood chips or straw being the most common in my experience.

You can scrape it off and toss it in the compost, leave it be, or have a little fun and explode it into brown powder by watering it like I did 😂

LEAF MINERS 🍂⛏ My young, fledgling citrus orchard is starting to get infested by leaf miners! This sounds like a pretty serious problem, but it’s actually not the biggest deal. 

Typically, on new citrus plantings you’re going to see quite a bit of leaf miner pressure at the start. Reason being, the larvae are only able to feed from a young leaves, which young trees have a lot of.

What tends to happen as the plants mature and the ecosystem starts to balance itself, is natural predators begin to come in and munch down on the leaf miners, while your trees get more mature (thus being able to handle some leaf miner damage)

If you really want them gone and you only have a few, you can squish them between your fingers.

node.text:
GARDEN FAILS 😂😭 I am no stranger to failing in the garden, let me tell you 😂

I was actually talking with @thebircharborgardens this week on the Epic Gardening podcast (go listen if you haven’t) about this idea of actually wanting to fail in the garden.

Seems ridiculous, right? Well it is, if you keep making the same mistakes over and over again. But given that we only have about 50 or 60 growing seasons in our entire life, it makes sense to try to grow as much as you can and as many different ways as possible if you’re trying to develop your green thumb.

This approach almost guarantees is you’re going to have a pretty high failure rate, but as long as you learn from those failures, your next seasons will be dramatically better than they would’ve been if you played it a little bit more conservatively!

If you have a hilarious garden fail, definitely share it below so we can all commiserate together 😭

🌶 SALSA GARDEN 🍅 This is one of my favorite beds in the garden right now!

I’ve got a few determinate tomatoes, four different types of peppers including the classic jalapeño but also some odd ones like a tequila sunrise and a mad hatter pepper.

Two different tomatillo varieties, you need to because they are not self fertile. You don’t have to have different varieties, you could just have two of the same one and you’ll be fine.

Carrots, green onions, basil, cilantro, papalo, and culantro (both good subs for cilantro if you’re finding it hard to grow) round out the bed, slotted into wherever there is space!

All of this fits perfectly in the Tall 8-in-1 bed, which is around 24sqft in this configuration (August preorders now open 👀)
